Archaeological remains suggest that a community has existed here for at least 4,000 years. 

In historical times, Chagford grew due to the wool trade and from tin mining in the area and in 1305 was made a stannary town where tin was traded.

The early 20th century Edward Lutyens house Castle Drogo lies nearby in Drewsteignton parish, and overlooks the town.

The poll placed it at the top of the rural list in The Sunday Times 2015 Best Places to Live guide. 

